 Kingdom"},"da":{"1175–":"1175–Afdød","1183–1242":"1183–1242","1220–1282":"1220–1282","1222–Male":"1222–Afdød","1175–Female":"1175–Afdød","1222":"1222","1220":"1220","1242":"1242","1175":"1175","1282":"1282","1183":"1183","Worthington, Lancashire, England":"Worthington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Worthington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Worthington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1175–":"1175–Overleden","1183–1242":"1183–1242","1220–1282":"1220–1282","1222–Male":"1222–Overleden","1175–Female":"1175–Overleden","1222":"1222","1220":"1220","1242":"1242","1175":"1175","1282":"1282","1183":"1183","Worthington, Lancashire, England":"Worthington, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Worthington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Worthington, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1175–":"1175–Deceased","1183–1242":"1183–1242","1220–1282":"1220–1282","1222–Male":"1222–Deceased","1175–Female":"1175–Deceased","1222":"1222","1220":"1220","1242":"1242","1175":"1175","1282":"1282","1183":"1183","Worthington, Lancashire, England":"Worthington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Worthington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Worthington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"England","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Middle English <i>Engelond</i> ‘England’. It was probably a formal alternative to   English  , which is also well evidenced as a surname in England. These names may have been acquired by English landowners who moved in Norman social circles or who lived in a neighbouring country (Scotland, Wales, or Ireland), or by English merchants who traded abroad.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of various farmsteads so named, from Old Norse <i>eng</i> ‘meadow’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’.","Swedish: ornamental name with the same meaning as 2."],"variants":[{"name":"English","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Welsh: ethnic name from Middle English <i>English</i>, <i>Inglish</i>, <i>Inglis</i> ‘English’ (Old English <i>Englisc</i>), sometimes alternating with Anglo-Norman French <i>Engleis</i>, <i>Engles</i>, <i>Anglais</i>, <i>Angles</i> (Old French <i>Englois</i>). Compare   Inglis   and   England  . Among the aristocracy and upper gentry it marked out a man of English ancestry from one of Norman or continental origin. In counties bordering England with Scotland and Wales the name distinguished an Englishman from a Scot or a native Welshman on both sides of the border. The name may also have been acquired by English merchants who traded abroad or who lived and worked in a ‘French’ borough in England (one exclusively administered by Normans).","Irish: in Ireland, this name was used to denote an Englishman, often being adopted for Irish <b>Aingléis</b> ‘Englishman’ or through mistranslation for <b>Mac an Ghallóglaigh</b>, see   Gallogly   and   Golightly  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice of England was born in 1175, in Worthington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. She married Knight Thomas de Worthington. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"1175–":"1175–Surnud","1183–1242":"1183–1242","1220–1282":"1220–1282","1222–Male":"1222–Surnud","1175–Female":"1175–Surnud","1222":"1222","1220":"1220","1242":"1242","1175":"1175","1282":"1282","1183":"1183","Worthington, Lancashire, England":"Worthington, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Worthington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Worthington, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1175–":"1175–Kuollut","1183–1242":"1183–1242","1220–1282":"1220–1282","1222–Male":"1222–Kuollut","1175–Female":"1175–Kuollut","1222":"1222","1220":"1220","1242":"1242","1175":"1175","1282":"1282","1183":"1183","Worthington, Lancashire, England":"Worthington, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Worthington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Worthington, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1175–":"1175–Décédée","1183–1242":"1183–1242","1220–1282":"1220–1282","1222–Male":"1222–Décédé","1175–Female":"1175–Décédée","1222":"1222","1220":"1220","1242":"1242","1175":"1175","1282":"1282","1183":"1183","Worthington, Lancashire, England":"Worthington, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Worthington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Worthington, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Alice of England est née en 1175, à Worthington, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a épousé Knight Thomas de Worthington. Ils ont eu au moins 2 fils."},"de":{"1175–":"1175–Verstorben","1183–1242":"1183–1242","1220–1282":"1220–1282","1222–Male":"1222–Verstorben","1175–Female":"1175–Verstorben","1222":"1222","1220":"1220","1242":"1242","1175":"1175","1282":"1282","1183":"1183","Worthington, Lancashire, England":"Worthington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","W